Tutorial 2 - Package Management and the Deno CLI

Tutorial 2 - Package Management and the Deno CLI

12 steps

In this tutorial, we will take you to an in-depth look at the new package registry created by the Deno team, known as the JavaScript Registry (JSR). We’ll explore its features, benefits, and how it seamlessly integrates into the Deno ecosystem.

As you progress through the tutorial, you will learn how to effectively manage packages and dependencies in Deno. This includes mastering the use of import maps, which simplify how you handle module imports, as well as familiarising yourself with several important Deno commands that will enhance your development workflow.

By the end of this tutorial, you should feel well-prepared for the journey ahead, equipped with the knowledge and skills needed to tackle your next project with confidence!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the 🆘 | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

⚠️ This campaign will only cover Linux or MacOS platforms. If you are a Windows user, please use GitHub Codespaces for a uniform and streamlined developer experience.

Prerequisites

  • Finished Quest 1
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Finished Quest 1
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Navigate the JSR
  • Explain the use cases of Import Maps
  • Use the commonly used Deno CLI commands

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 12

  • Step 1: Javascript Registry (JSR)

    Watch first the following video

    For now, you should ignore the part where you publish a package to the Javascript Registry (JSR). You don't want to add unnecessary traffic to a public registry with dummy packages. In the future, if you have plans to publish a package, you can head to https://jsr.io/docs/introduction for a quick walk-through.

    Let's just focus on what JSR is.

    The Javascript Registry or the JSR is like the public npm registry. The website for JSR is https://jsr.io. It aims to be a public and community-managed registry that allows users to publish Javascript and Typescript code as packages or modules.

    The Javascript Registry features automatic documentation generation, package scoring called "JSR Score", file and directory list metadata, dependencies list metadata, and runtime compatibility metadata.

    For example, head over to https://jsr.io/@oak/oak.

    You will see a lot of information such as the overview, the runtime this package supports (e.g. Deno, Bun, or Node), and how well managed, well trusted and well documented the package is indicated by the JSR Score.

    Head over to https://jsr.io/@oak/oak/doc. This is the Docs section. You will see information about classes, interfaces, types, functions, function parameters and parameter types, and function return types. Although, for new developers, this is too arcane, experienced developers will love to have these kinds of documentation to understand how all of the code works, avoiding the need to read the entirety of the source code.

    It is also good for package or library developers as well because any code changes they did are reflected in the Docs.

  • Step 2: Importing a dependency

    At this point, you already should have generated a Deno project first from Tutorial 1. If you haven't, please head over to Tutorial 1 and then come back here for further instructions.

    Using a dependency in Deno comes in four ways:

    • Using local imports
    • Using import syntax
    • Using HTTP imports
    • Using import maps

    Each of the following requires some understanding, hence, they are in separate steps. Let's start with the first point which is importing local modules and files.

  • Step 3: Importing local modules and files

    At the root directory of your project, let's create a file called multiply-words.ts. Write the following code to your multiply-words.ts.

    export function mutiplyWords(word: string, times: number): string {
  let words: string = "";
  for (let count = 0; count < times; count++) {
    words = words.concat(word).concat(" ");
  }
  words.trim();
  return words;
}
    TypeScript

    Next, replace your main.ts code with the following code.

    import { mutiplyWords } from "./multiply-words.ts";

if (import.meta.main) {
  const multipliedWords = mutiplyWords(Deno.args[0].trim(), Number.parseInt(Deno.args[1].trim()));
  console.log(multipliedWords)
}
    TypeScript

    Here, you have imported the function multiplyWords from the multiply-words.ts file. Deno needs it to be explicit that it's a file import with a path specifier ./. So if your multiply-words.ts file is located in, let's say, a utils directory, the path specifier will also look different. It will look like the code below instead.

    import { mutiplyWords } from "./utils/multiply-words.ts";

if (import.meta.main) {
  const multipliedWords = mutiplyWords(Deno.args[0].trim(), Number.parseInt(Deno.args[1].trim()));
  console.log(multipliedWords)
}
    TypeScript

    with the following directory structure in VSCode.

    You have written your first CLI tool with this code. Deno.args is a standard function that takes user inputs indicated as separate arguments using whitespaces. Try running the following command.

    deno run main.ts wk 100

    It should give you 100 times of "wk" as output on your terminal.

    The only difference between Node and Deno when it comes to file imports is that Deno requires you to be explicit with the file extension as opposed to Node.

    Another thing to consider with file imports is it becomes unwieldy when you have to import it to multiple parts of a project, especially as it grows as a developing codebase.

  • Step 4: Import Syntax

    Users can use a package using the import syntax. You can see the import syntax in action in the following code snippet. Try this out by writing this code snippet and replacing all of the contents of your main.ts code.

    import { Application, Router } from "jsr:@oak/oak";
const router = new Router();
const app = new Application();

router.get("/", (ctx) => {
    ctx.response.body = "Hello, World!";
})

app.use(router.allowedMethods());
app.use(router.routes());

if (import.meta.main) {
    app.listen({ port: 8080 });
}
    TypeScript

    Line 1 shows how your import syntax is written. By default, it looks for the latest version, but this is not ideal as you might get a version that contains breaking changes. To avoid that, you can make sure to specify a version with a version specifier @17.1.3.

    import { Application, Router } from "jsr:@oak/oak@17.1.3";
const router = new Router();
const app = new Application();

router.get("/", (ctx) => {
    ctx.response.body = "Hello, World!";
})

app.use(router.allowedMethods());
app.use(router.routes());

if (import.meta.main) {
    app.listen({ port: 8080 });
}
    TypeScript

    Also notice that there is a jsr: specifier here. What this specifier does is to tell Deno that our package comes from the JSR. Try running the following command on the terminal.

    deno run main.ts

    If this does not work the first time, try running the following commands.

    deno install --entrypoint main.ts
deno run main.ts

    The first command installs the imported packages declared in the import syntax to cache.

    Type "y" on all of the prompts. Now on another terminal, run the following curl command.

    curl "http://127.0.0.1:8080/"

    You should get a "Hello, World!" output. This means it's working!

    Do you remember that Deno now has node/npm compatibility? Let's try that in the following code snippet. Write the following code to main.ts replacing all of its contents.

    import express from "npm:express@4.21.1";
const app = express();

app.get("/", (_req, res) => {
        res.send("Hello, World!");
});

if (import.meta.main) {
        app.listen({ port: 8080 });
}
    TypeScript

    Before, you tried @oak/oak from the JSR. Now, the new code snippet imports an npm package called express with a version specifier @4.21.1 on Line 1. You also know that it is from npm because of the npm: specifier. Without this specifier, running the code will error.

    Try running the following command on the terminal.

    deno run main.ts

    If this does not work the first time, try running the following commands.

    deno install --entrypoint main.ts
deno run main.ts

    The first command installs the imported packages declared in the import syntax to cache.

    Type "y" on all of the prompts. Now on another terminal, run the following curl command.

    curl "http://127.0.0.1:8080/"

    You should get a "Hello, World!" output. This means it's also working!

    You might notice a lot of differences between the number of prompts as well. By default, npm and node require almost all access to your network and file system.

    This does not make sense for code that just wants to run a simple HTTP server that contains no code that requires read or write access to the file system. This is why Deno has all of the prompts as it detects these when you run the code using express.

    But packages like oak, which started as a Deno-focused project, only need access when it's required such as the network. This means Deno has fewer prompts as compared to the code with express.

  • Step 5: HTTP Imports

    Deno also supports HTTP Imports. HTTP Imports are much like file imports except they're fetched via HTTP and the import is a URL to that file. For example, this secret GitHub Gist https://gist.github.com/uncomfyhalomacro/b5de275dfcbaeff1d2d89739541e4e6f can be imported to our main.ts like the code below.

    import { hello } from "https://gist.githubusercontent.com/uncomfyhalomacro/b5de275dfcbaeff1d2d89739541e4e6f/raw/648e323e4ab872cc2a6eeafdd1ccf46d8f6c6301/mod.ts";

if (import.meta.main) {
  hello();
}
    TypeScript

    Replace your main.ts from the above code snippet and run the following command.

    deno run main.ts

    It should output "Hello Stacker!" on your terminal.

    Although HTTP Imports are a nice addition, they are only useful for one-time use functions or libraries within a file. They're not good if a project gets larger since you will write multiple HTTP Imports all over your codebase.

    They also do not have clear versioning so you won't be able to determine when they introduce breaking changes.

    They're also a security risk as importing files through HTTP may introduce malicious code changes without the knowledge of the user. Users should take caution and avoid HTTP imports and are encouraged to use only packages from the package registries such as the JSR or npm package registry, or write their variant of the functions from the HTTP Imports.

  • Step 6: Import Maps

    Deno also supports Import Maps. Import Maps is a web standard. You can see it documented here in MDN Docs. An Import Map is a key-value pair in JSON format where the key is the aliased name of the value which is the imported module.

    Import Maps makes it easy to import modules, functions, libraries, and packages all over your codebase. They also make it easy to manage versions as well if you want to convert all your import syntax as an import map.

    Let's attempt to use the examples, starting from Step 3.

    At the root directory of your project, open your deno.json file.

    You can already see that it already contains an import map to @std/assert. Now let's add an import map to multiply-words.ts. Just below the @std/assert import map, add an import map to it and name the key as multiply-words. Check the code snippet below if you have done it correctly. Be careful that you do not forget to add a comma after @std/assert.

    {
  "tasks": {
    "dev": "deno run --watch main.ts"
  },
  "imports": {
    "@std/assert": "jsr:@std/assert@1",
    "multiply-words": "./multiply-words.ts"
  }
}
    JSON

    Next, open and edit main.ts. Replace all of its contents with the following code below.

    import { mutiplyWords } from "multiply-words";

if (import.meta.main) {
  const multipliedWords = mutiplyWords(Deno.args[0].trim(), Number.parseInt(Deno.args[1].trim()));
  console.log(multipliedWords)
}
    TypeScript

    You can see here that our import syntax has changed. It now points to our import map multiply-words.

    Try running the following command.

    deno run main.ts wk 100

    It should give you 100 times of "wk" as output on your terminal.

    Import Maps make it easy to manage packages from different registries, and package versions. In Step 4, you tried both oak and express. Let's create an import map for both of them.

    Open your deno.json file. Make sure you write and copy the code below to ensure that you did it correctly.

    {
  "tasks": {
    "dev": "deno run --watch main.ts"
  },
  "imports": {
    "@std/assert": "jsr:@std/assert@1",
    "multiply-words": "./multiply-words.ts",
    "@oak/oak": "jsr:@oak/oak@17.1.3",
    "express": "npm:express@4.21.1"
  }
}
    JSON

    Can you guess what the code examples will be in Step 4 now that you have introduced import maps? Head to our Discord forum channel and share the code!

    Lastly, also try to add an import map for Step 5. Can you also guess what the new code will look like? Head to our Discord forum channel and share the code!

  • Step 7: Adding Dependencies | Essential Deno Commands

    To add dependencies in Deno, you learned that you have to write it manually as a

    • File Import 
    • Import Syntax
    • HTTP Imports
    • Import Map

    But there is a better way and that is with the deno add command. For example, let's delete the file deno.json. Now run the following commands.

    touch deno.json
deno add jsr:@oak/oak

    You will have a file created and then modified with an import map of the latest version of oak like the screenshot below.

    However, deno add only supports adding dependencies from package registries such as from the JSR and NPM. It does not support File Imports and HTTP Imports.

    Take note that you also must specify the "source" registry specifiers, jsr: or npm:. Otherwise, it won't work like the screenshot below.

    You can also specify versions when adding. Let's add npm:express@4.21.1 with deno add.

    deno add npm:express@4.21.1

    Your file should have been modified and created an import map of express like the screenshot below.

    You can also declare dependencies as developer dependencies by passing a --dev flag. Developer dependencies are subjective to most developers but they usually mean dependencies that are used only for development and NOT for production. For example, one can add a developer dependency for tests such as @std/assert. Run the command below to try it out. 

    deno add --dev jsr:@std/assert

    You should see that @std/assert is now in the dictionary of import maps.

    ⚠️ For now, there is still confusion and an open issue about the --dev flag since there is no clear separation in deno.json about whether a dependency is a dev dependency or not, or if there needs to be a separation. There is an open issue on Deno's source repository regarding this. This information might change in the future.

  • Step 8: Formatting Code | Essential Deno Commands

    Deno out of the box contains a code formatter. Replace all of the contents of your main.ts file and copy the following code.

    import { mutiplyWords } from "./multiply-words.ts";

if (import.meta.main) {
  const multipliedWords = 
  mutiplyWords(Deno.args[0].trim(), 
  Number.parseInt(Deno.args[1].trim()));
                  console.log(
                    
                    
                    multipliedWords)
}
    TypeScript

    Then run the following command.

    deno fmt

    This should format your code into a much readable format like the screenshot below.

    No need to install third-party formatters like prettier. Deno has it out of the box! 📦

  • Step 9: Linting Code | Essential Deno Commands

    Deno also has a built-in linter. Linting is a process of checking code for potential ambiguities such as possible wrong use of a type, declaring a variable with the let keyword but is only used once, or unused variables.

    Try out Deno's linting capabilities by first replacing all the main.ts code with the following code.

    function foo(s: any): any {
  return "foo"
}

if (import.meta.main) {
  let foobar = "bar";
  const barsoap = 0;
  console.log(foo("foo"), foobar);
}
    TypeScript

    Then run the following command.

    deno lint

    You should have a similar output message like the screenshot below, telling you how to fix your code.

    Although the Deno plugin comes with a Language Server (LSP) that does allow us to check that something in our code is wrong, deno lint exists to check all of your files in the codebase so you can track them at a glance 🙂.

  • Step 10: Watch Flag | Essential Deno Commands

    Deno also has a built-in "watcher". A watcher is a utility that reruns a program if it detects file or directory changes.

    Let's try that in Deno. Replace all of your main.ts code with the following code.

    if (import.meta.main) {
  Deno.serve((_req_) => {
    (async () => {
      for await (const el of Deno.readDir(".")) {
        console.log(el.name);
      }
    })();
    const hello = new Response("Hello, World!");
    return hello;
  });
}
    TypeScript

    Now try running the following command.

    deno run -A --watch main.ts

    You should be able to see on your terminal that your HTTP server is running. Now try changing the word "World" to "Stackie". You should see a message that the watcher has detected a file change and has restarted the deno run command.

    🤔 VSCode by default tries to save the files automatically in some user settings so do not be surprised if you have not pressed Save and still get the Watcher's detect file change message.

    Having this option is great when you are trying to update code. Deno has watcher capabilities on most commands such as fmt, lint, and run.

  • Step 11: Upgrading and Downgrading Deno | Essential Deno Commands

    Deno also comes with a version manager. You can upgrade Deno by running the following command.

    deno upgrade

    To downgrade, one can specify a version. For example, if you want to specify a version because you just want to downgrade, you can run.

    deno upgrade 2.0.1

    You can check that it works by checking that you have a different version of Deno after running the following command.

    deno --version

    However, do note that this depends on how you installed Deno. If you have installed Deno using another package manager such as apt, brew, or winget, you won't be able to easily upgrade or downgrade.

    For example, the screenshot below attempts to upgrade Deno which was installed through another package manager.

    There are workarounds, of course, like running the command as root user (which is not advisable and not recommended) or adding the output flag. Here is an example of using the output flag below.

    deno upgrade --output ~/.local/bin/deno

    You can then run your other version of deno as long as ~/.local/bin is part of your PATH environmental variable.

    Amazing! You have finished this tutorial and learned a lot about Deno 🦕

    You are finally ready to take part in the next quest! The next quest is to create a practical project using Deno as the runtime for backend server development.
